JOHANNESBURG – The Democratic Alliance (DA) is demanding that the National Prosecuting Authority (NPA) reinstate 18 charges relating to 783 counts of fraud, corruption, and money-laundering against President Jacob Zuma. Thursday is the deadline for both the party and President Zuma to make representations. The DA says if the charges are not reinstated, NPA's credibility will suffer. READ: Zuma corruption charges: presidency questions audit report It says the decision must be made by a court of law and not a public servant. The charges relate to payments made to Zuma by controversial businessman, Schabir Shaik. Last year, the North Gauteng High Court, ruled the decision to drop the charges was irrational. eNCA